1

00:00:02,549  -->  00:00:06,160
You might not have noticed but in the previous lesson on

2

00:00:06,160  -->  00:00:10,570
linear regression your predicted response variable was not constrained at all.

3

00:00:10,570  -->  00:00:14,760
That means, that with the right inputs it was possible to predict the house that

4

00:00:14,759  -->  00:00:19,464
has a negative price or that the height of an individual is 80 feet.

5

00:00:19,464  -->  00:00:22,765
Using logistic regression as opposed to linear regression,

6

00:00:22,765  -->  00:00:26,335
bounds our response to a probability between zero and one,

7

00:00:26,335  -->  00:00:29,964
rather than any possible value like you saw with linear regression.

8

00:00:29,964  -->  00:00:32,835
Mathematically, to perform logistic regression,

9

00:00:32,835  -->  00:00:35,350
we need to change the labels of fraud or not,

10

00:00:35,350  -->  00:00:40,730
success or failure and the other variables to only a one and zero outcome.

11

00:00:40,729  -->  00:00:42,789
So, in the credit card transaction example,

12

00:00:42,789  -->  00:00:45,039
you could call all the fraud cases one,

13

00:00:45,039  -->  00:00:48,174
while all the non-fraud cases would be zero values.

14

00:00:48,174  -->  00:00:51,584
Then, logistic regression is set up in a way where

15

00:00:51,585  -->  00:00:56,505
our linear model will predict the log odds instead of predicting the response itself.

16

00:00:56,505  -->  00:00:59,950
Here, P is the probability of a one value occurring.

17

00:00:59,950  -->  00:01:02,800
So, this is a ratio of a probability of an event

18

00:01:02,799  -->  00:01:06,579
occurring as compared to the probability of the event not occurring.

19

00:01:06,579  -->  00:01:09,549
This is called the odds ratio and by taking

20

00:01:09,549  -->  00:01:12,759
the log and equating this to our linear regression line,

21

00:01:12,760  -->  00:01:17,484
we control our predictions to be between zero and one for the probability of a success.

22

00:01:17,484  -->  00:01:19,090
With a bit of algebra,

23

00:01:19,090  -->  00:01:22,000
you can change the equation using the log odds to look

24

00:01:22,000  -->  00:01:25,719
like this and this solves for probability directly.

25

00:01:25,719  -->  00:01:27,965
This function here is called the sigmoid.

26

00:01:27,965  -->  00:01:30,640
The sigmoid function takes the value from

27

00:01:30,640  -->  00:01:35,560
your linear regression line and maps it between zero and one as a probability.

28

00:01:35,560  -->  00:01:37,689
Both of these equations are commonly

29

00:01:37,689  -->  00:01:40,799
used to understand the setup for logistic regression.

30

00:01:40,799  -->  00:01:42,250
Let us get some practice with this.
